Predicting Personal Loan Acceptance using Neural Networks
Overview
This project focuses on predicting the acceptance of personal loans by customers using neural networks. The dataset contains various features related to customers' demographics, financial status, and banking behavior. Through careful analysis and modeling, we aim to build a predictive model that can assist financial institutions in identifying potential loan customers.

Dataset Description
The dataset consists of both categorical and continuous features:

Categorical Features:
Personal Loan: Indicates whether the customer accepted the personal loan offered in the last campaign.
Securities Account: Whether the customer has a securities account with the bank.
CD Account: Whether the customer has a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank.
Online: Whether the customer uses internet banking services.
Credit Card: Whether the customer uses a credit card issued by UniversalBank.

Continuous Features:
Age: Age of the customer.
Experience: Years of professional experience.
Income: Annual income in dollars.
CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards.
Mortgage: Mortgage value of the customer's house.
Ordinal Categorical Features:
Family: Family size of the customer.
Education: Education level of the customer.
Methodology
Data Preprocessing:

Removed irrelevant features such as customer ID and zip code.
Conducted basic statistical analysis to understand the distribution of variables.
Data Splitting:

Divided the dataset into training and testing sets to evaluate model performance accurately.
Feature Scaling:

Standardized the continuous features to ensure they were on the same scale, which is crucial for neural networks.
Model Training:

Utilized a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) classifier, a type of neural network, to construct the predictive model.
Tuned the architecture of the neural network, including the number of hidden layers and neurons per layer, and activation functions for optimal performance.
Model Evaluation:

Evaluated the model's performance using metrics such as accuracy and F1 Score.
Achieved impressive results with an accuracy of approximately 98.1% and an F1 Score of about 89.84%.
Conclusion
This project demonstrates the effectiveness of neural networks in predicting personal loan acceptance based on customer attributes. By leveraging advanced machine learning techniques, financial institutions can make informed decisions regarding loan approvals, thereby optimizing their operations and enhancing customer satisfaction.

For further inquiries or discussions about this project, feel free to reach out. Let's continue exploring innovative solutions through artificial intelligence and machine learning!
